```cpp
struct TreeNode {
    int data;
    TreeNode *left, *right;
    TreeNode(int x) : data(x), left(NULL), right(NULL) {}
};
```

The function `solution` should delete the target node and return the modified binary tree. Note that the tree nodes are not manually allocated with `new`, and instead, a recursive `createTree` helper function is provided to create and populate the tree with node values.

### Constraints

* The binary tree nodes are not manually allocated with `new`. Instead, use the `createTree` function to create and populate the tree.

### Example

```cpp
TreeNode* root = createTree({8,3,10,1,6,null,14,null,null,4,7,15});
TreeNode* newRoot = solution(root, 3);
assert(newRoot->data == 8);
assert(newRoot->left == solution(root->left, 1)/* returns new root of left subtree */);
assert(newRoot->right == solution(root->right, 14)/* returns new root of right subtree */);
```

